          "id": "organizational-behavior-401-l04-c2",
          "title": "Burke-Litwin Causal Model",
          "content": "W. Warner Burke and George Litwin created a detailed model that helps us understand how different parts of an organization work together. This model identifies twelve important factors that can influence how an organization operates and changes. These factors are divided into three main categories: transformational factors, transactional factors, and individual factors. Transformational factors include things like the external environment, the organization's mission and strategy, leadership styles, and the overall culture of the organization. These factors are crucial because they drive significant changes from the top levels of management down to all employees. On the other hand, transactional factors involve everyday management practices, the organizational structure, systems in place, and the climate within work units. These factors affect how things run on a daily basis. Lastly, individual factors focus on personal aspects such as motivation, individual needs and values, task requirements, and how both individual and organizational performance are measured. The Burke-Litwin model teaches us that for an organization to achieve lasting change, it is essential to first address the transformational factors. If an organization tries to change its structure without also considering its culture and leadership, it is likely to encounter challenges and may not succeed. This highlights the importance of taking a comprehensive approach when managing organizational change, ensuring that all aspects are aligned and supportive of the desired outcomes.\nContext recap: W. Warner Burke and George Litwin created a detailed model that helps us understand how different parts of an organization work together. This model identifies twelve important factors that can influence how an organization operates and changes. These factors are divided into three main categories: transformational factors, transactional factors, and individual factors.\nWhy this matters: Burke-Litwin Causal Model helps learners in Business connect ideas from Organizational Design & Change Management to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
